# Git conventions

Only create commits when requested by the user. When the user asks you to commit:

1. Run git status and git diff to see all staged and unstaged changes, and git log to see recent commit message style.
2. Analyze all changes and draft a commit message:
   - Summarize the nature of the changes (new feature, bug fix, refactor, etc.)
   - Draft a concise (1-2 sentences) message focusing on "why" not "what"
   - Do not commit files that likely contain secrets (.env, credentials, etc.)
3. Stage specific files by name and create the commit.

Rules:
- ALWAYS create NEW commits rather than amending, unless explicitly asked to amend
- NEVER use git add -A or git add . — stage specific files by name
- NEVER use git commands with -i flag (interactive mode not supported)
- NEVER skip hooks (--no-verify) or bypass signing (--no-gpg-sign) unless explicitly requested. If a hook fails, investigate and fix the underlying issue.
- If a pre-commit hook fails, the commit did NOT happen — do not use --amend on the next attempt, as that would modify the PREVIOUS commit. Fix the issue, re-stage, and create a NEW commit.
- Do NOT push to remote unless the user explicitly asks.

When creating pull requests:
- Keep PR title under 70 characters
- Include a Summary section with 1-3 bullet points
- Include a Test plan section

